TY  - JOUR
AU  - Falato, Antonio
AU  - Favara, Giovanni
AU  - Scharfstein, David
T1  - Bank Risk-Taking and the Real Economy: Evidence from the Housing Boom and Its Aftermath
PY  - 2026
Y1  - 2026/02/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhaf091
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 39
IS  - 2
SP  - 427
EP  - 458
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - During the U.S. housing credit boom, publicly traded banks increased mortgage lending activity and relaxed standards much more than privately held banks. The increase in risk had real effects for a variety of county-level aggregates including employment and consumption. Cross-sectional evidence and a quasi-experiment indicate that the increase in risk stemmed from the institutional ownership and the equity compensation of publicly traded banks, in turn leading banks to place greater weight on short-term equity performance. These results are consistent with the view that a focus on short-term earnings and stock prices amplifies boom–bust credit cycles, in turn leading to real cycles for the aggregate economy.
Y2  - 4/24/2026
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhaf091
ER  - 




